00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:56.170
So I call the book SUBLIMINAL: How Your Unconscious
Mind Rules Your Behavior. Why did I call it

00:04:56.170 --> 00:05:00.770
SUBLIMINAL? Well some of you may know that
in the 1950's a marketing consultant named

00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:08.470
James Vickery said that he was able to subliminally
influence people's behavior by flashing for

00:05:08.470 --> 00:05:14.300
just one-thirtieth of a second a sign that
says either, "Drink Coca-Cola" or "Eat popcorn,"

00:05:14.300 --> 00:05:21.400
during a movie called Picnic that was playing
in a New Jersey movie theater. And he claimed

00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:29.290
that he could increase the sales of popcorn
by I think it was 18% and Coke was 51 or 55%

00:05:29.290 --> 00:05:35.520
by having these subliminal messages play in
front of the audience which they did not perceive.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:41.650
But about five years later, this is the 50th
anniversary of an article in Advertising Age

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:46.720
Magazine in which he admitted that it was
all a hoax; he had a failed marketing business

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:50.390
and he was trying to prop it up with this
trick. But although he admitted that it was

00:05:50.390 --> 00:05:56.740
a hoax it never really left the American consciousness
or our culture and so subliminal persuasion

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:01.610
is something that everyone even still recognizes
today.

00:06:01.610 --> 00:06:06.970
Some people follow this and don't seem to
have gotten the retraction though, including

00:06:06.970 --> 00:06:11.449
one of our former Presidents. This was an
ad that George Bush ran against Al Gore in

00:06:11.449 --> 00:06:15.780
which he flashed, or his campaign, flashed
the word rats in the middle of a message for

00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:23.430
one-thirtieth of a second and this message
played on TV over an anti-Gore ad and it played

00:06:23.430 --> 00:06:29.140
for about 4,000 times before somebody discovered
it and then it was pulled from the air. So

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:32.449
apparently they didn't really get the message.

00:06:32.449 --> 00:06:37.020
But actually a few years after this a scientist
decided to test to see whether such subliminal

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:41.300
messages can actually have an effect on people
and they found that even a message such as

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:46.920
this or other messages about drinks can have
a little effect, a fragile effect on people

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:48.450
in the laboratory.

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:52.660
For instance, in one experiment people were
brought into a room and told that they were

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:57.130
gonna see word scrambles and unbeknownst to
them one of the quote word scrambles really

00:06:57.130 --> 00:07:02.490
said Lipton Ice. And afterwards the subjects
were offered drinks and far more than who

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:07.360
had seen the Lipton Ice chose Lipton Iced
Tea than those who hadn't seen it.

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:10.320
But nobody really believed you can persuade
someone to like Lipton Iced Tea if you don't

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:16.710
like Lipton Iced Tea or that that effect would
last beyond the laboratory hours later; it's

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:20.220
really something that's hard to reproduce
in the lab and it's very fragile but it does

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:21.220
exist.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:25.270
One other hand there are many subliminal effects
in your environment that are affecting you

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:29.150
all the time that are much less artificial
than this, and that's really what the book

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:33.820
is about. It's about subliminal effects, meaning
effects that go on below the threshold of

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:38.760
consciousness that your brain picks up, that
your senses pick up, that are processed by

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:43.111
the unconscious part of your brain and feed
into your consciousness perceptions, visual

00:07:43.111 --> 00:07:48.290
perceptions, social perceptions, memories,
and they govern the way you behave to a great

00:07:48.290 --> 00:07:49.690
extent.

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:55.280
Let me, before I talk about them specifically,
let me define what I mean by unconscious behavior.

00:07:55.280 --> 00:08:00.350
An unconscious process in your mind is something
that is automatic and occurs with no effort

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:04.720
on your part and it's outside of your awareness,
you're not aware that it's happening or that

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:09.400
it's influencing you, and it's outside of
your will and largely outside of your control.

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:18.449
So those are the traits that I mean when I
say something is unconscious.

00:08:18.449 --> 00:08:23.230
And as a result of that we often don't understand
what's influencing us in our everyday lives

00:08:23.230 --> 00:08:26.139
[pause]

00:08:26.139 --> 00:08:30.910
and however I wanna point out that the unconscious
I'm talking about is not the Freudian unconscious

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:35.500
that you may have heard a lot of about, it's
not the unconsciousness that was talked about

00:08:35.500 --> 00:08:39.990
for most of the 20th century; this is a totally
different kind of unconscious. The Freudian

00:08:39.990 --> 00:08:44.560
unconscious was very emotional and it was
hidden from people for motivational reasons.

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:48.690
But the new unconscious that neuroscientists
and psychologists talk about is far different

00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:53.080
from that; it's not accessible through therapy
or talking or introspection, but it takes

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:57.610
place in parts of your brain that are inherently
inaccessible to your conscious mind. So even

00:08:57.610 --> 00:09:01.839
though Freud was right that a lot of your
behavior is influenced by the unconscious,

00:09:01.839 --> 00:09:05.580
